written cantonese and mandarin are the same. spoken cantonese and mandarin are distinctly different, as cantonese has 8 to 9 tones and mandarin only has 4. homynyms have completely different meanings in the dialects.

one of my mandarin speaking instructors told a little story to the class. a man was riding on the train and realized his "hai" had fallen off. he yells to the conductor, "stop the train! stop the train! my "hai" fell off!" the conductor immediately stopped the train and the man jumped off to retrieve his "hai". upon returning, the conductor saw that the man had retrieved his shoes. In mandarin, "hai" means son, in cantonese it means shoe.

